Yes, indeed. Here's the "canonical" C strlen translated to unsafe Go with pointer arithmetic:<p><pre><code>  package main

  import (
  	"fmt"
  	"unsafe"
  )

  func strlen(b []byte) int {
  	str := uintptr(unsafe.Pointer(&b[0]))
  	s := str
  	for ; *(*byte)(unsafe.Pointer(s)) != 0; s++ {}
  	return int(s - str)
  }

  func main() {
  	fmt.Println(strlen([]byte("ho ho ho\000")))
  }

</code></pre>
Not that anyone should use it :-)<p>The safe and readable variant of this, often used in Go code, is "slice arithmetic", like this: <a href="http://golang.org/src/pkg/crypto/sha256/sha256.go#L105" rel="nofollow">http://golang.org/src/pkg/crypto/sha256/sha256.go#L105</a>
